## Summary

Implemented **US-013: Reveal-strategy setting** (Bringr-93j.13) — the user can now choose how "other" apps/windows get out of the way when hovering the wheel.

**What I built:**
- `RevealStrategy` enum (`raiseToFront` / `hideOthers` / `dimOthers`, default **hide-others**) — persisted and read fresh per summon, mirroring the existing `InteractionMode`/`RadialAppearance` pattern.
- `WindowController` now dispatches the active strategy onto its primitives at **both** levels via `revealApp(_:)`/`revealWindow(_:)` (the navigator's two reveal call sites switched to these):
  - **raise** — activate the app / AX-raise the window, hiding nothing;
  - **hide** — the existing minimize/hide behaviour;
  - **dim** — raise the target plus a spotlight overlay (`Dimming` seam → `LiveDimmer`, a reused click-through `NSPanel`) that darkens the desktop with the target window(s) punched out. `restore()` clears the dim; `restoreWindows(of:)` re-cuts it to the app's windows when leaving the sub-wheel.
- A "Reveal" radio-group section in Preferences; `RadialMenuController` reads a `strategyProvider` at summon, so a change applies on the next summon without relaunch.

**Quality gates:** build SUCCEEDED · `swiftlint --strict` 0 violations · 200 tests pass (16 new, confirmed executing) · app launches and runs without crashing.

**Honest limitation:** the dim/raise *visuals* and hover sweep need a human (real mouse-chord/trackpad trigger, Accessibility permission, real windows) and can't be verified headlessly — so the strategy *dispatch* (which operations fire, with which frames) is fully covered by `FakeDimmer`-backed unit tests instead. Also noted: a concurrent iteration's app-commit work merged into the tree mid-session, so I re-read files before editing.

